Neto Global Design System Rules
Core Mission: Every page must feel premium, ultra-minimalist, and functionally intuitive, following the Apple Design Philosophy.

1. Visual Foundation (The Atmosphere)
Canvas: Use a Light Gray background (#F5F5F7) for the main body. NEVER use bg-slate-50/50 or similar Tailwind opacity variants.

Surfaces: All content containers must be Pure White (#FFFFFF) with a 24px "Squircle" (continuous) corner radius (rounded-3xl).

Elevation: Avoid heavy shadows. Use a subtle 4% opacity drop shadow with a wide blur to create a soft "lift": box-shadow: 0 4px 20px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.08).

Dividers: Use whitespace as the primary separator. If a line is necessary, it must be 1px solid #F7F7F8 (Ice Cream).

2. Typography & Color Identity
Primary Font: Nunito (Strictly). Use var(--font-nunito) or font-family: 'Nunito', system-ui, sans-serif.

Text Hierarchy:

Main Values/Titles: Blueberry (#303150), Bold (700). Use var(--text-primary) or #303150 directly.

Subtext/Labels: Steel Gray (#7E7F90), Regular weight (400). Use var(--text-secondary) or #7E7F90 directly.

Light Text: Light Grey (#BDBDCB). Use var(--text-light) or #BDBDCB directly.

Functional Palette:

Positive/Active: Turquoise (#0DBACC).

Negative/Urgent: Cotton Candy Pink (#F18AB5).

Flow/Neutral: Baby Blue (#74ACEF).

Primary Action: Dodger Blue (#69ADFF).

Typography Scale:
- Hero (Major values like Net Worth): 2.5rem (40px), Bold (700), Blueberry (#303150)
- Page Title: 1.5rem (24px), Bold (700), Blueberry (#303150)
- Section Title: 1.5rem (24px), Bold (700), Blueberry (#303150)
- Card Title: 1.125rem (18px), Semi-bold (600), Blueberry (#303150)
- Body Text: 0.9375rem (15px), Regular (400), Blueberry (#303150)
- Label: 0.8125rem (13px), Medium (500), Steel Gray (#7E7F90)
- Small Text/Caption: 0.75rem (12px), Regular (400), Light Grey (#BDBDCB)

3. Spacing & Layout
Padding: Minimum 24px-32px (1.5rem-2rem) for content containers. Use p-6 (24px) or p-8 (32px) as standard.

Gaps: Use gap-6 (24px) for sections, gap-4 (16px) for related items, gap-2 (8px) for tight spacing.

Margins: Use mb-8 (32px) for section headers, mb-6 (24px) for card spacing, mb-4 (16px) for element spacing.

Page Content Padding: Use p-4 lg:p-6 (16px mobile, 24px desktop) for main content area.

4. Border Radius Guidelines
Main Containers/Cards: Always use rounded-3xl (24px / 1.5rem). This is the "Squircle" standard.

Buttons: Use rounded-xl (12px / 0.75rem) for all buttons.

Inputs/Selects/Textareas: Use rounded-xl (12px / 0.75rem) for form elements.

Icons/Small Elements: Use rounded-lg (8px / 0.5rem) for small interactive elements.

NEVER use rounded-lg or rounded-2xl for main content containers - always rounded-3xl.

5. Buttons
Primary Button (.btn-primary):
- Background: Dodger Blue (#69ADFF)
- Hover: #5A9EE6
- Text: White
- Padding: px-5 py-2.5 (20px horizontal, 10px vertical)
- Border Radius: rounded-xl (12px)
- Font: Nunito, Medium weight
- Shadow: shadow-sm on default, shadow-md on hover
- Disabled: opacity 0.6, cursor not-allowed

Secondary Button (.btn-secondary):
- Background: White (#FFFFFF)
- Border: 1px solid #F7F7F8 (Ice Cream)
- Text: Blueberry (#303150)
- Hover Background: #F7F7F8
- Padding: px-5 py-2.5
- Border Radius: rounded-xl (12px)
- Font: Nunito, Medium weight

Icon Button (.btn-icon):
- Background: Transparent
- Text: Steel Gray (#7E7F90)
- Hover Background: #F7F7F8
- Padding: p-2 (8px)
- Border Radius: rounded-lg (8px)

6. Forms & Inputs
Input (.input):
- Background: White (#FFFFFF)
- Border: 1px solid #E8E8ED
- Border Radius: rounded-xl (12px)
- Padding: px-4 py-3 (16px horizontal, 12px vertical)
- Text Color: Blueberry (#303150)
- Placeholder Color: Light Grey (#BDBDCB)
- Focus Border: Dodger Blue (#69ADFF)
- Focus Ring: rgba(105, 173, 255, 0.2)
- Font: Nunito

Select (.select):
- Same as Input, with appearance-none and cursor-pointer

Label (.label):
- Text Color: Steel Gray (#7E7F90)
- Font: Nunito, Medium weight (500)
- Font Size: 0.875rem (14px)
- Margin Bottom: mb-1.5 (6px)

Textarea: Same styling as Input, with resize-none for controlled sizing.

7. Modals
Modal Overlay (.modal-overlay):
- Background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5)
- Backdrop Filter: blur(4px)
- Position: Fixed, full screen
- Z-index: 9999
- Padding: 1rem (16px)

Modal Content (.modal-content):
- Background: White (#FFFFFF)
- Border Radius: rounded-3xl (24px) - NOT rounded-2xl
- Shadow: shadow-xl
- Max Width: max-w-md (28rem) for standard modals
- Max Height: max-h-[90vh] with overflow-y-auto

Modal Header (.modal-header):
- Padding: p-6 (24px)
- Border Bottom: 1px solid #F7F7F8

Modal Body (.modal-body):
- Padding: p-6 (24px)
- Gap: space-y-4 (16px vertical)

Modal Footer (.modal-footer):
- Padding: p-6 (24px)
- Border Top: 1px solid #F7F7F8
- Gap: gap-3 (12px horizontal)

8. Loading States
Spinner: Use Dodger Blue (#69ADFF) for primary loading indicators.

Loading Text: Steel Gray (#7E7F90), Regular weight.

Skeleton Loaders: Use Light Grey (#BDBDCB) with subtle animation.

Loading Container: Center content vertically and horizontally, use appropriate spacing.

9. Error States
Error Text: Cotton Candy Pink (#F18AB5) for error messages.

Error Background: Light pink background (rgba(241, 138, 181, 0.1)) for error containers.

Error Border: 1px solid rgba(241, 138, 181, 0.3).

Validation: Show errors immediately on blur, use subtle animations.

10. Icons
Size Guidelines:
- Small Icons: w-4 h-4 (16px) for inline text icons
- Standard Icons: w-5 h-5 (20px) for buttons and UI elements
- Large Icons: w-6 h-6 (24px) for emphasis
- Hero Icons: w-8 h-8 (32px) or larger for major visual elements

Color Guidelines:
- Default: Steel Gray (#7E7F90)
- Primary Actions: Dodger Blue (#69ADFF)
- Success: Turquoise (#0DBACC)
- Error: Cotton Candy Pink (#F18AB5)
- Hover: Match parent element hover state

Stroke Width: Use strokeWidth={1.75} for standard icons, strokeWidth={2} or {2.5} for emphasis.

11. Color Usage Guidelines
NEVER use Tailwind slate/gray colors (text-slate-*, bg-slate-*, border-slate-*). Always use design system colors:

Text Colors:
- text-[#303150] or var(--text-primary) for primary text
- text-[#7E7F90] or var(--text-secondary) for secondary text
- text-[#BDBDCB] or var(--text-light) for light text

Background Colors:
- bg-[#F5F5F7] for main canvas (NOT bg-slate-50/50)
- bg-[#FFFFFF] for content containers
- bg-[#F7F7F8] for hover states and dividers (NOT bg-slate-100)

Border Colors:
- border-[#F7F7F8] for dividers
- border-[#E8E8ED] for input borders
- border-[#69ADFF] for focus states

12. Interaction & UX Principles
The "Ghost" Standard: All scrollbars must have a transparent track and a thin (4px), rounded thumb with 10% idle opacity, increasing to 60% on hover.

Information Density: Prioritize legibility. If a page feels crowded, increase padding (minimum 24px-32px) and simplify the elements.

Interactive Feedback: Use scale-up (1.05) and soft colored glows instead of traditional tooltips or pop-ups.

RTL-First: All layouts must be built natively for Hebrew, ensuring proper alignment of currency symbols (₪) and text flow.

13. Engineering Constraints for Cursor
Fluid Units Only: Use rem, vw/vh, and %. Prohibit the use of fixed px for layout dimensions to ensure perfect responsiveness.

Component Logic: Keep components modular and reusable.

Edge Case Handling: Implement "Edge Fades" (gradient masks) and "Partial Peeks" for all scrollable content to signal that more data exists below the fold.

CSS Variables: Prefer using CSS variables (var(--text-primary), var(--text-secondary)) when available in globals.css, otherwise use direct hex values (#303150, #7E7F90).

Class Usage: Use utility classes from globals.css (.btn-primary, .input, .card) when available, otherwise implement styles directly following these guidelines.

14. Floating Elements
Position: Use position fixed with z-index 50 for floating UI (same level as QuickAddFab). Modals use z-index 9999.

Shadow: Use shadow-[0_4px_20px_rgba(0,0,0,0.08)] (identical to card elevation).

Backdrop: Use backdrop-blur-sm with bg-white/95 for expanded floating panels (glassmorphism).

Spacing from edges: Minimum 1rem (16px) from all viewport edges.

Max width: 22rem (352px) for floating panels to avoid dominating the screen.

Responsive padding: px-4 on mobile, px-6 on desktop.

Enter animation: slideUp + fadeIn, 300ms ease-out.

Exit animation: slideDown + fadeOut, 200ms ease-in.

Hover: scale 1.02 with transition 200ms.

15. Progress Indicators
Circular Progress:
- Size: 2.5rem (40px) for compact views, 3.5rem (56px) for expanded views
- Stroke width: 4px
- Track color: #E8E8ED (Light Gray)
- Completed fill: #0DBACC (Turquoise)
- In-progress fill: #69ADFF (Dodger Blue)
- Animation: stroke-dasharray transition 800ms ease-out
- Pulse: scale 1.05 to 1.1 every 2 seconds when updating

Linear Progress:
- Height: 0.25rem (4px)
- Border radius: rounded-full
- Colors: same as circular
- Animation: width transition 500ms ease-out

16. Micro-Interactions
Button Hover:
- Scale: 1.02 to 1.05
- Glow: shadow-lg using the button color
- Transition: 200ms ease-out
- Active state: scale 0.98

Card Hover:
- Scale: 1.01 to 1.02
- Shadow: elevate from shadow-sm to shadow-md
- Transition: 200ms ease-out

Icon Animation:
- Rotation: plus/minus 5deg on hover
- Scale: 1.1 on click
- Transition: 150ms ease-out

Progress Update:
- Pulse: scale 1.1 then back to 1.0 over 300ms
- Color flash: opacity 0.8 to 1.0 over 200ms

17. Celebration Animations
Confetti:
- Particle count: 20 to 30 colored particles
- Colors: #0DBACC, #69ADFF, #F18AB5, #E9A800
- Duration: 2000ms
- Easing: ease-out
- Spread: 360deg from origin point

Success Checkmark:
- SVG path animation using stroke-dasharray and stroke-dashoffset
- Duration: 600ms
- Easing: ease-out
- Scale sequence: 0 to 1.2 to 1.0

Toast Notification:
- Position: top-center, z-index 10000
- Background: #0DBACC with opacity 0.95
- Animation: slide down + fade in over 300ms
- Auto-dismiss: 3000ms
- Shadow: shadow-xl

18. Cultural Sensitivity
NEVER use pig-related icons (PiggyBank, pig emojis, etc.) anywhere in the application — this is a religiously observant (Haredi) user base. Use alternatives for savings/balance concepts:
- Coins (preferred for balance/savings cards)
- CircleDollarSign
- Banknote
- Wallet

19. Dropdowns Inside Modals — React Portal Pattern
Dropdowns (and any absolutely-positioned floating UI) rendered inside a modal WILL be clipped by the modal's overflow unless rendered outside the DOM subtree. Always use React Portal (createPortal) for custom dropdowns inside modals.

Implementation pattern:
1. Place a ref on the trigger button to measure its position: `const triggerRef = useRef<HTMLButtonElement>(null)`
2. On open, read `triggerRef.current.getBoundingClientRect()` and store `{ top: rect.bottom + scrollY + 4, left: rect.left + scrollX, width: rect.width }`
3. Render the dropdown list via `createPortal(<div style={{ position: 'absolute', top, left, width, zIndex: 10000 }} />, document.body)`
4. Close on click-outside by checking both the trigger container and the portal element (find by id or a separate ref)
5. Close on scroll/resize if needed to prevent stale positions

This pattern also applies to: tooltips, context menus, autocomplete lists, and any other floating panel that appears inside a modal or an overflow:hidden container.

20. Custom Dropdowns — NEVER Use Native `<select>`
The native HTML `<select>` element renders a browser-default dropdown popup that CANNOT be styled and looks out of place in the design system. ALWAYS use a custom dropdown component instead.

Use `StyledSelect` (`@/components/ui/StyledSelect`) for simple value pickers:
- Portal-based dropdown (follows rule 19)
- Matches design system: Nunito font, correct colors, rounded-xl, focus ring
- Supports `size="sm"` for compact contexts (modals, inline forms)
- Supports disabled state, placeholder, aria-label

Use `CategorySelect` (`@/components/ui/CategorySelect`) for category pickers with icons:
- Full icon + color support via CategoryInfo
- Add/edit/delete custom categories
- Goal category support

Implementation:
```tsx
// Simple picker
<StyledSelect
  value={selected}
  onChange={setSelected}
  placeholder="בחר..."
  options={[{ value: 'a', label: 'אפשרות א' }]}
  size="sm"
/>

// Category picker
<CategorySelect
  value={selected}
  onChange={setSelected}
  defaultCategories={expenseCategories}
  customCategories={customCats}
/>
```

This rule applies everywhere: modals, forms, settings, filters. If you see a native `<select>`, replace it.

21. RTL Icon + Text Buttons
In buttons containing both an icon and text, the icon must appear on the RIGHT side of the text (the "start" side in RTL is the right).
- In JSX with a flex container, place the TEXT first and the ICON after it. RTL flex will visually render the icon to the right of the text.
- Correct: `<button className="flex items-center gap-2">הוסף <Plus /></button>`
- Wrong: `<button className="flex items-center gap-2"><Plus /> הוסף</button>`
- This applies to all buttons across the entire app, including: primary, secondary, and any other buttons that combine text + icon.

22. Monday.com-Style Data Tables & Zero-Friction UX Patterns
Based on our Roadmap and CFO Dashboard implementations, these patterns create a premium, high-density data management experience.

22.1 CSS Grid Tables (Never HTML `<table>`)
- ALWAYS use CSS Grid (`grid grid-cols-[...]`) for data tables, never HTML `<table>` elements.
- Define consistent column templates shared between headers and rows: `grid-cols-[40px_minmax(250px,_1fr)_120px_140px_140px]`
- Headers: `bg-[#FAFAFA] border-b border-[#E8E8ED]` with `text-xs font-semibold text-[#7E7F90]`
- Rows: White background (`bg-white`), subtle bottom border (`border-b border-gray-200`), hover state (`hover:bg-gray-50`)
- Cell padding: `px-4 py-3` for headers, `px-4 py-2.5` for data cells
- RTL: Use logical properties (`ps-`/`pe-` instead of `pl-`/`pr-`, `start-0` instead of `left-0`)

22.2 Inline Editing (Zero-Click-to-Edit)
- Clicking any editable cell (title, amount, date, category) immediately transforms it into an `<input>` or `<input type="date">`
- No "Edit" button needed — the cell IS the input when clicked
- Save on `blur` or `Enter` key press
- Visual feedback: Subtle border highlight (`border-indigo-400`) when editing
- Auto-focus: Use `useEffect` to focus the input when entering edit mode
- Escape key: Cancel edit and restore original value

22.3 Optimistic UI Updates with Rollback
- Update local state IMMEDIATELY when user performs an action (create, update, delete)
- Call server action in the background
- On success: Replace temporary/optimistic data with real server response (especially IDs)
- On failure: Rollback to previous state snapshot and show error toast
- Pattern:
```tsx
const prevDataRef = useRef<DataType | null>(null);
const saveSnapshot = () => { prevDataRef.current = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(data)); };
const rollback = (msg?: string) => {
  if (prevDataRef.current) { setData(prevDataRef.current); prevDataRef.current = null; }
  if (msg) showError(msg);
};
// In handler:
saveSnapshot();
setData(optimisticUpdate); // Immediate UI update
try {
  const serverResult = await serverAction();
  setData(replaceOptimisticWithReal(serverResult)); // Sync IDs
} catch { rollback('Error message'); }
```

22.4 Quick-Add Rows (The "Monday" Input Method)
- At the bottom of each table, render a special row that looks like a normal row but displays "+ הוסף [item]" text
- Clicking it activates an input in the title/name cell
- Pressing Enter creates a new record with sensible defaults (e.g., `amount: 0`, `status: 'ACTIVE'`, `type: 'EXPENSE'`)
- After creation, focus moves to the next editable cell (e.g., amount) for immediate data entry
- Use `forwardRef` and `useImperativeHandle` to expose an `activate()` method for programmatic triggering
- Pattern:
```tsx
const AddRow = forwardRef<{ activate: () => void }, Props>((props, ref) => {
  const [isCreating, setIsCreating] = useState(false);
  useImperativeHandle(ref, () => ({ activate: () => setIsCreating(true) }));
  // ... render input when isCreating, otherwise "+ הוסף" text
});
```

22.5 Portal-Based Dropdowns for Badges/Status
- Status, Priority, Type badges are full-width rectangles within their grid cells
- Clicking a badge opens a portal-based dropdown (using `createPortal` to `document.body`)
- Dropdown positioned via `getBoundingClientRect()`: `top: rect.bottom + 6, left: rect.left`
- Close on outside click (check both trigger ref and dropdown ref)
- Close on scroll/resize to prevent stale positions
- RTL-aware: Use `dir="rtl"` on dropdown container
- Z-index: `z-[10000]` for dropdowns
- Styling: `bg-white rounded-xl py-1 px-2` with `box-shadow: 0 4px 24px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.12)`

22.6 Row Hover Actions (Delete, More Options)
- Delete button (trash icon) appears ONLY on row hover (`group-hover:block` or conditional rendering)
- Position: Far end of row (rightmost in RTL), subtle gray (`text-gray-400`) that turns red on hover (`hover:text-red-500`)
- Use `group` class on row container and `group-hover:` utilities for child elements
- Pattern:
```tsx
<div className="group ...">
  {/* row content */}
  <button className="opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity">
    <Trash2 className="w-4 h-4 text-gray-400 hover:text-red-500" />
  </button>
</div>
```

22.7 Filtering & Sorting Toolbar
- Position: Above data tables, below summary/KPI cards
- Layout: Flex container with `gap-3`, RTL-aware (`dir="rtl"`)
- Search Input: Full-width with `Search` icon, `max-w-[320px]`, placeholder "חפש..."
- Filter Button: Shows active filter count badge when filters are applied
- Sort Buttons: Separate sort controls per table (subscriptions vs transactions) with independent configs
- Clear Filters: Subtle text button (X icon) that appears only when filters/search are active
- All dropdowns use portal pattern (see 22.5)

22.8 Memoized Data Processing (Filter → Sort)
- Use `useMemo` hooks to process raw data through filters and sorting
- Order of operations: 1) Search filter, 2) Type filter, 3) Status filter, 4) Category filter, 5) Sort
- Dependencies: Include all filter/sort state variables and raw data arrays
- Pattern:
```tsx
const filteredData = useMemo(() => {
  let result = [...rawData];
  // Apply filters in sequence
  if (searchQuery) result = result.filter(/* search logic */);
  if (filterType !== 'ALL') result = result.filter(/* type logic */);
  if (filterStatus.length > 0) result = result.filter(/* status logic */);
  // Sort
  result.sort((a, b) => {
    const dir = sortDirection === 'asc' ? 1 : -1;
    switch (sortKey) {
      case 'title': return a.title.localeCompare(b.title, 'he') * dir;
      case 'amount': return (a.amount - b.amount) * dir;
      case 'date': return (new Date(a.date).getTime() - new Date(b.date).getTime()) * dir;
    }
  });
  return result;
}, [rawData, searchQuery, filterType, filterStatus, sortKey, sortDirection]);
```

22.9 Badge Styling (Status, Priority, Type)
- Full-width, full-height rectangles within their grid cells
- Background color from constants (e.g., `STATUS_COLORS[status]`)
- White text (`text-white`), centered (`flex items-center justify-center`)
- Rounded corners: `rounded` (4px) or `rounded-md` (6px)
- Font: `text-xs font-medium`
- Pattern:
```tsx
<div className="w-full h-8 rounded flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-medium text-white" style={{ backgroundColor: COLORS[value] }}>
  {LABELS[value]}
</div>
```

22.10 Drag-and-Drop (For Kanban/Task Boards)
- Use `@hello-pangea/dnd` (React DnD Kit successor)
- Wrap board in `<DragDropContext onDragEnd={handleDragEnd}>`
- Each group/column: `<Droppable droppableId={groupId}>`
- Each draggable item: `<Draggable draggableId={itemId} index={index}>`
- On drag end: Update `orderIndex` fields and call server action to persist
- Visual feedback: Slight opacity change (`opacity-50`) while dragging
- RTL: Ensure drag handles and visual feedback work correctly in RTL layout

22.11 Independent Sort Configurations
- When multiple tables exist on the same page (e.g., subscriptions and transactions), each table should have its own independent sort configuration
- State: `sortConfigSubscriptions` and `sortConfigTransactions` with different keys (e.g., `nextBillingDate` vs `date`)
- UI: Separate sort buttons/dropdowns per table
- Defaults: Set sensible defaults (e.g., subscriptions by `nextBillingDate` asc, transactions by `date` desc)

22.12 Filter State Management
- Unified filter config object: `{ type: 'ALL' | 'INCOME' | 'EXPENSE', status: string[], category: string }`
- Status array: Can include multiple statuses (checkboxes), unified across different record types
- Category: Single selection (radio/pill buttons), dynamically extracted from data
- Clear filters: Reset all filter state to defaults (`type: 'ALL', status: [], category: ''`)
- Active filter count: Calculate as `(type !== 'ALL' ? 1 : 0) + status.length + (category ? 1 : 0)`

22.13 View Toggle (Table vs Timeline/Gantt)
- Use tabs or toggle buttons to switch between views
- State: `currentView: 'table' | 'timeline'`
- Both views share the same filtered/sorted data
- Timeline view: Fixed-width, horizontally scrollable, shows exactly 3 months at a time
- RTL timeline: Time flows right-to-left, use `right` and `width` percentages for positioning

22.14 Empty States
- When filtered data is empty, show centered message: "אין [items] להצגה" or "אין מספיק נתונים להצגת תרשים"
- Styling: `text-sm text-[#7E7F90]`, centered with `flex items-center justify-center`
- Height: Match typical row height (e.g., `py-8`)

22.15 Date Formatting (Hebrew Locale)
- Use `Intl.DateTimeFormat` with Hebrew locale: `new Intl.DateTimeFormat('he-IL', { ... }).format(date)`
- Short format: `{ day: 'numeric', month: 'short' }` → "12 במרץ"
- Long format: `{ day: 'numeric', month: 'long', year: 'numeric' }` → "12 במרץ 2024"
- RTL: Dates automatically align correctly in RTL layout

22.16 Currency Formatting
- Use `Intl.NumberFormat` with ILS currency: `new Intl.NumberFormat('he-IL', { style: 'currency', currency: 'ILS' }).format(amount)`
- Or use project utility: `formatCurrencyAmount(amount, 'ILS')`
- RTL: Currency symbol (₪) automatically positions correctly

22.17 ID Synchronization (Critical for Optimistic UI)
- When creating new records optimistically, assign a temporary ID (e.g., `temp_sub_${Date.now()}`)
- After server action resolves, find the optimistic record by temporary ID and replace it with the real server response
- This ensures immediate editing of newly created items works correctly
- Pattern:
```tsx
const tempId = `temp_${Date.now()}`;
setData([...data, { id: tempId, ...optimisticData }]);
const serverResult = await createAction(data);
setData(data.map(item => item.id === tempId ? serverResult : item));
```

22.18 High-Density Information Display
- Tables should feel information-dense but not cramped
- Use consistent spacing: `px-4 py-2.5` for cells, `gap-4` between columns visually
- Font sizes: `text-sm` for data, `text-xs` for labels/badges
- Truncate long text: `truncate` class with `min-w-0` on flex containers
- Tooltips: Show full text on hover for truncated cells (optional enhancement)

22.19 Real-Time Search (Debounced Optional)
- Search input filters data in real-time as user types
- For large datasets, consider debouncing (300ms) to avoid excessive filtering
- Search across multiple fields: `title`, `category`, and optionally other relevant fields
- Case-insensitive: Use `.toLowerCase()` for both query and data

22.20 Grouped Data (Task Groups, Categories)
- Visual grouping: Use colored left border (`border-r-4` in RTL) matching group color
- Group headers: Sticky or visually distinct, show group title and column headers
- Group summary: Optional progress bar or count at bottom of group
- Collapsible groups: Optional feature to expand/collapse groups (future enhancement)